d; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mawd ferch Rhys was born about 1374, in Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Jenkin ap Jenkin. She died after 1410."},"et":{"about 1374–after 1410":"umbes 1374–pärast 1410","1370–1410":"1370–1410","1411–1441":"1411–1441","1418–Female":"1418–Surnud","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1374–1410":"1374–1410","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1441":"1441","ABT 1411":"umbes 1411","1374":"1374","about 1374":"umbes 1374","1370":"1370","1418":"1418","after 1410":"pärast 1410","Of Pwll Dyfach, Aber-Nant, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Abernant, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Pwll, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1374–after 1410":"noin 1374–1410 jälkeen","1370–1410":"1370–1410","1411–1441":"1411–1441","1418–Female":"1418–Kuollut","1420–Female":"1420–Kuollut","1374–1410":"1374–1410","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1441":"1441","ABT 1411":"noin 1411","1374":"1374","about 1374":"noin 1374","1370":"1370","1418":"1418","after 1410":"1410 jälkeen","Of 